<DocsLayout title="Wewaran Cycles - Balinese Calendar" description="Understanding the Balinese week-based cycles">
	<h1 class="font-display text-4xl gold-accent mb-8">Wewaran Cycles</h1>

	<p class="text-lg mb-6">
		Wewaran are the various week-based cycles that operate simultaneously in the Balinese calendar system.
	</p>

	<h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-balinese-gold mt-12 mb-6">The Nine Wewaran</h2>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Ekawara (1-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">The simplest cycle, always <strong>Luang</strong>.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Dwiwara (2-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Alternates between two days: <strong>Menga</strong> and <strong>Pepet</strong>.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Triwara (3-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Three days: <strong>Pasah</strong>, <strong>Beteng</strong>, and <strong>Kajeng</strong>.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Caturwara (4-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Four days: <strong>Sri</strong>, <strong>Laba</strong>, <strong>Jaya</strong>, and <strong>Menala</strong>.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Pancawara (5-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Five days: <strong>Umanis</strong>, <strong>Paing</strong>, <strong>Pon</strong>, <strong>Wage</strong>, and <strong>Kliwon</strong>. Important for market days.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Sadwara (6-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Six days: <strong>Tungleh</strong>, <strong>Aryang</strong>, <strong>Urukung</strong>, <strong>Paniron</strong>, <strong>Was</strong>, and <strong>Maulu</strong>.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Saptawara (7-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Seven days: <strong>Redite</strong>, <strong>Soma</strong>, <strong>Anggara</strong>, <strong>Buda</strong>, <strong>Wraspati</strong>, <strong>Sukra</strong>, and <strong>Saniscara</strong>. Most commonly used.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Astawara (8-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Eight days: <strong>Sri</strong>, <strong>Indra</strong>, <strong>Guru</strong>, <strong>Yama</strong>, <strong>Ludra</strong>, <strong>Brahma</strong>, <strong>Kala</strong>, and <strong>Uma</strong>.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Sangawara (9-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Nine days: <strong>Dangu</strong>, <strong>Jangur</strong>, <strong>Gigis</strong>, <strong>Nohan</strong>, <strong>Ogan</strong>, <strong>Erangan</strong>, <strong>Urungan</strong>, <strong>Tulus</strong>, and <strong>Dadi</strong>.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Dasawara (10-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Ten days derived from Pancawara × Saptawara urip combination.</p>

